      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="india-epidemic">
        <span class="section-tag">India Context</span>
        <h2>India's Silent Deficiency Epidemic: Why We Are So Vulnerable</h2>

        <p>India paradoxically suffers some of the world's highest rates of Vitamin D deficiency despite being a tropical country with abundant sunshine year-round. Studies published in the <em>Indian Journal of Endocrinology and Metabolism</em> estimate that <strong>between 50–90% of Indians</strong> across all age groups, geographic regions, and socioeconomic backgrounds are deficient in Vitamin D3.</p>

        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Risk Factor</th>
              <th>Why It Causes D3 Deficiency</th>
              <th>Why It Causes B12 Deficiency</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Vegetarian / Vegan Diet</td>
              <td>Few plant foods contain D3</td>
              <td>B12 found almost exclusively in animal products</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Indoor Lifestyle</td>
              <td>Skin needs UVB sunlight to synthesize D3</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Dark Skin Tone</td>
              <td>Melanin reduces UVB absorption efficiency</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Ageing (40+)</td>
              <td>Skin's D3-conversion capacity declines</td>
              <td>Stomach acid needed for B12 absorption decreases</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Sunscreen Use</td>
              <td>SPF 15+ blocks >95% of D3 synthesis</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Antacid / PPI Medications</td>
              <td>Reduce calcium absorption</td>
              <td>Block intrinsic factor needed for B12 uptake</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Metformin (Diabetes Drug)</td>
              <td>—</td>
              <td>Directly reduces B12 absorption by 30%</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Obesity</td>
              <td>D3 stored in fat tissue, less available in blood</td>
              <td>—</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>The compounding effect of multiple risk factors — for example, a vegetarian Indian woman over 50 who works indoors, takes antacids, and uses sunscreen — can result in <strong>profoundly low levels of both nutrients</strong> simultaneously, creating a perfect storm for accelerating bone loss and joint degeneration that is entirely misattributed to normal ageing.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">🔬</div></div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="diagnosis">
        <span class="section-tag">Getting Diagnosed</span>
        <h2>How Deficiency is Properly Diagnosed</h2>

        <p>Diagnosis requires specific blood tests that must be actively requested — they are <strong>not part of a routine complete blood count</strong> (CBC) panel. If you ask for a general blood test without specifying these markers, you will not receive them.</p>

        <div class="info-card gold">
          <div class="info-card-title">
            <div class="info-card-icon icon-gold">🩸</div>
            Tests to Request From Your Doctor
          </div>
          <table class="compare-table" style="margin:12px 0 0;">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Test</th>
                <th>What It Measures</th>
                <th>Optimal Range</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>25(OH)D / Vitamin D Total</td>
                <td>Active Vitamin D3 in blood</td>
                <td>40–60 ng/mL (not just "normal" 20+)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Serum Vitamin B12</td>
                <td>Circulating B12 levels</td>
                <td>300–900 pg/mL (deficiency &lt;200)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Serum Homocysteine</td>
                <td>Indirect B12 / folate status</td>
                <td>&lt;10 µmol/L</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Serum Calcium</td>
                <td>Calcium regulation</td>
                <td>8.5–10.5 mg/dL</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>PTH (Parathyroid Hormone)</td>
                <td>Bone calcium regulation</td>
                <td>10–65 pg/mL</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>DEXA Scan</td>
                <td>Bone mineral density (T-score)</td>
                <td>T-score above −1.0</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <div class="warning-icon">⚠️</div>
          <p><strong>Important:</strong> Many laboratories flag a Vitamin D level of 20 ng/mL as "normal." Most orthopaedic and endocrine specialists now recommend a target of <strong>40–60 ng/mL</strong> for optimal bone health and immune function. Do not accept a borderline report as reassurance — discuss optimal targets with your specialist.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="section-divider"><div class="divider-icon">💊</div></div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <section class="article-section fade-up" id="recovery">
        <span class="section-tag">Treatment</span>
        <h2>Treatment & Your Path to Recovery</h2>

        <p>The good news: these deficiencies are correctable. With the right protocol, many patients begin experiencing meaningful improvement in joint pain, energy levels, and mobility within <strong>6–12 weeks</strong>. The key is a structured, monitored approach — not self-supplementation based on generic advice.</p>

        <ol class="steps-list">
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">01</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Comprehensive Blood Panel</div>
              <p>Get baseline levels of D3, B12, homocysteine, PTH, and calcium before starting any supplementation. This allows your doctor to track your progress and adjust dosages.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">02</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Loading Phase (4–12 Weeks)</div>
              <p>Severely deficient patients typically require high-dose D3 (60,000 IU/week or as prescribed) and B12 injections (methylcobalamin 1000 mcg) to rapidly restore depleted stores.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">03</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Co-factor Support</div>
              <p>Vitamin K2 (MK-7) is essential alongside D3 to direct calcium into bones rather than arteries. Magnesium is required to convert D3 to its active form. These are often missing from basic supplements.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">04</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Maintenance Supplementation</div>
              <p>After achieving optimal levels, a daily maintenance protocol is established — typically D3 1000–2000 IU/day with K2, and oral B12 500–1000 mcg/day for most adults.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">05</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Follow-up Testing (Every 3–6 Months)</div>
              <p>Blood levels must be rechecked regularly to confirm correction and avoid toxicity — particularly for D3, where excessive levels (above 100 ng/mL) can cause hypercalcaemia.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="step-item">
            <div class="step-num">06</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <div class="step-title">Physiotherapy & Weight-Bearing Exercise</div>
              <p>Nutritional correction must be paired with supervised exercise to stimulate bone remodelling and rebuild muscle strength around affected joints for lasting recovery.</p>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ol>

        <div class="info-card navy">
          <div class="info-card-title">
            <div class="info-card-icon icon-navy">🚫</div>
            Why You Should Never Self-Supplement Without Testing
          </div>
          <p style="margin:0; font-size:0.9rem; color:var(--text-lt);">Vitamin D toxicity (hypervitaminosis D) is a real and serious condition that can cause kidney stones, nausea, confusion, and dangerous calcium buildup in soft tissues. It cannot occur from sunlight, but can occur from excessive supplementation. Always confirm deficiency with blood tests and supplement under medical supervision with regular monitoring.</p>
        </div>
