        <h2>When to See an Orthopedic Specialist — Not Just Your GP</h2>

        <p>While a general physician can order blood tests and initiate supplementation, certain presentations require the evaluation of an <strong>orthopedic specialist</strong> who can assess the impact of deficiency on your specific joint and bone architecture, and integrate nutritional correction with any needed structural intervention.</p>

        <p>See an orthopaedic specialist if you experience any of the following:</p>

        <div class="symptom-grid">
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">Joint pain that hasn't responded to 4+ weeks of physiotherapy or pain medication</div></div>
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">A fracture from minor trauma or a fall from standing height (fragility fracture)</div></div>
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">Progressive loss of height (suggests vertebral compression fracture)</div></div>
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">Inability to climb stairs or rise from a chair without using your arms</div></div>
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">Nerve symptoms — tingling, numbness — alongside bone or joint pain</div></div>
          <div class="symptom-item"><div class="symptom-icon si-red">!</div><div class="symptom-text">A DEXA scan showing T-score below −1.0</div></div>
        </div>

        <p style="margin-top:24px;">The combination of an accurate diagnosis, corrected nutritional deficiencies, targeted physiotherapy, and — where structurally necessary — minimally invasive orthopaedic intervention offers the majority of patients a genuine, lasting path to pain relief and improved function. <strong>Age is not your sentence. Deficiency might be your diagnosis.</strong></p>
      </section>

